{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem is a Trie-based optimization problem. To prevent identity theft, no ID can be a prefix of another. This is equivalent to ensuring that in a Trie containing all final IDs, no leaf node is an ancestor of another leaf node. We need to find the minimum number of bits to append to existing strings to satisfy this property.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "trie_construction_and_prefix_analysis",
      "instructions": "Build a Trie from the given N bitstrings. For each node in the Trie, track whether it represents the end of one of the original IDs. Identify all nodes that are 'terminal' (the end of an original ID). For each terminal node, determine if it is an ancestor of another terminal node in the original set. This identifies the initial conflicts."
    },
    {
      "label": "greedy_cost_optimization",
      "instructions": "Given the Trie structure where some terminal nodes are ancestors of others, we need to move the 'descendant' terminal nodes to new positions by appending bits. For each terminal node that is an ancestor of another, we must append bits to the descendant to push it into a new branch. Calculate the minimum bits required to ensure that for every original ID, no prefix of its modified version is the full modified version of another ID. This can be modeled as finding the minimum cost to make all terminal nodes leaves in the Trie."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should use the Trie structure to identify which IDs are currently prefixes of others. The total cost is the sum of bits needed to extend each 'offending' ID such that it no longer matches any existing ID's prefix. Specifically, for every node in the Trie that is a terminal node and has descendants that are also terminal nodes, we must extend the descendants. The optimal strategy involves a greedy approach or a bottom-up traversal to count the minimum bits needed to 'branch off' from the current paths."
}

